---
import MainLayout from '../layouts/MainLayout.astro';
import StepGenerator from '../components/quantum/StepGenerator.astro';
---

<MainLayout
  title="Quantum Walk - A Thought Experiment"
  description="Explore the Quantum Walk: a deterministic time-step sequence inspired by the Many Worlds interpretation of quantum mechanics."
>
  <!-- Hero Section -->
  <section class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-16">
    <div class="text-center mb-16">
      <h1 class="text-5xl md:text-6xl font-bold mb-6">
        Quantum Walk
      </h1>
      <p class="text-xl text-star-white/80 max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        A deterministic, infinitely reproducible sequence of time steps,
        starting from the Unix Epoch. Each step is calculated by hashing
        the previous timestamp and converting it to a duration (0-7 days).
      </p>
      <p class="text-lg text-cosmic-purple mt-4 max-w-2xl mx-auto">
        A speculative thought experiment: could a matching sequence from
        an unknown source suggest an origin from another branch of the universe?
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Step Generator Component -->
    <StepGenerator />

    <!-- What is This Section -->
    <div class="mt-20 bg-cosmic-black/60 backdrop-blur-sm rounded-2xl p-8 border border-cosmic-blue/30">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold mb-6 text-center text-cosmic-blue">What is the Quantum Walk?</h2>

      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto space-y-6 text-star-white/80">
        <p>
          The <strong class="text-star-white">Quantum Walk</strong> is a deterministic algorithm that generates
          an irregular but fully reproducible sequence of timestamps. It works as follows:
        </p>

        <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-3 ml-4">
          <li>
            <strong class="text-cosmic-purple">Start at Unix Epoch (0)</strong> - January 1, 1970, 00:00:00 UTC
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong class="text-cosmic-purple">Hash the current timestamp</strong> using SHA-256
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong class="text-cosmic-purple">Convert the hash to a duration</strong> between 0 and 7 days
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong class="text-cosmic-purple">Add the duration</strong> to get the next timestamp
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong class="text-cosmic-purple">Repeat</strong> infinitely
          </li>
        </ol>

        <p>
          Because the algorithm uses cryptographic hashing (SHA-256) and runs entirely client-side
          in your browser, the sequence is <em class="text-cosmic-blue">identical everywhere</em>.
          Anyone running this algorithm will generate the exact same sequence.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-cosmic-purple/10 border border-cosmic-purple/30 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3 text-cosmic-purple">The Thought Experiment</h3>
          <p class="text-star-white/80">
            Inspired by the Many Worlds interpretation of quantum mechanics
            (see <a href="/theory" class="text-cosmic-blue hover:underline">Theory</a>),
            this experiment asks: <em>If we detected an external signal with a matching
            subsequence of intervals, and we could confirm it wasn't generated locally,
            might it suggest an origin from a parallel branch sharing the same deterministic root?</em>
          </p>
          <p class="text-star-white/60 text-sm mt-3">
            This is purely speculative—not scientific proof. It's a conceptual illustration.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Quick Actions -->
    <div class="mt-12 grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <a
        href="/matcher"
        class="bg-cosmic-purple/20 hover:bg-cosmic-purple/30 border border-cosmic-purple/50 rounded-xl p-8 transition-all hover:shadow-glow-purple group"
      >
        <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-3 text-cosmic-purple">Match a Sequence</h3>
        <p class="text-star-white/70">
          Input your own sequence of timestamps or intervals and compare them
          to the Quantum Walk to find the best alignment and similarity score.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-4 text-cosmic-purple group-hover:translate-x-1 transition-transform inline-flex items-center">
          Try the Matcher →
        </div>
      </a>

      <a
        href="/about"
        class="bg-cosmic-blue/20 hover:bg-cosmic-blue/30 border border-cosmic-blue/50 rounded-xl p-8 transition-all hover:shadow-glow-blue group"
      >
        <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-3 text-cosmic-blue">Learn More</h3>
        <p class="text-star-white/70">
          Read about the concept, the algorithms behind it, and the Many Worlds
          interpretation that inspired this thought experiment.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-4 text-cosmic-blue group-hover:translate-x-1 transition-transform inline-flex items-center">
          Read About It →
        </div>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>
</MainLayout>
